1. What is List?
👉 The List interface in Java is a part of the Java Collections Framework that represents an ordered collection of elements.

Position in Hierarchy:

Iterable
   ↓
Collection
   ↓
List  ← (Focus here)
Classes like ArrayList, LinkedList, Vector, Stack implement List

3. Key Characteristics of List:
 Maintains insertion order
 Allows duplicate elements
 Allows null values
 Supports index-based access
 Dynamic size (can grow/shrink)

4. Important Methods in List
🔹 Adding Elements
add(E e)
add(int index, E element)
🔹 Removing Elements
remove(int index)
remove(Object o)
🔹 Accessing Elements
get(int index)
set(int index, E element)
🔹 Searching
indexOf(Object o)
lastIndexOf(Object o)
🔹 Size
size()

What is ArrayList?
ArrayList is a resizable array implementation of the List interface in Java that allows duplicate elements and provides 
fast random access.

Key Features of ArrayList
✔ Dynamic size (automatically grows/shrinks)
✔ Maintains insertion order
✔ Allows duplicates
✔ Allows null values
✔ Fast access using index
❌ Not synchronized (not thread-safe by default)

Important Methods in ArrayList
🔹 1. Adding Elements
add(E e)
add(int index, E element)

👉 Example:

list.add("A");
list.add(1, "B");
🔹 2. Removing Elements
remove(int index)
remove(Object o)

👉 Example:

list.remove(0);
list.remove("A");
🔹 3. Accessing Elements
get(int index)

👉 Example:

list.get(1);
🔹 4. Updating Elements
set(int index, E element)

👉 Example:

list.set(1, "C");
🔹 5. Size of List
size()
🔹 6. Searching
contains(Object o)
indexOf(Object o)
lastIndexOf(Object o)
🔹 7. Iteration Methods
for loop
for-each loop
Iterator
ListIterator
🔹 8. Clearing Elements
clear()
🔹 9. Checking Empty
isEmpty()
🚀 Example Program
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

        list.add("Java");
        list.add("Python");
        list.add("Java"); // duplicate allowed

        System.out.println(list.get(1)); // Python

        list.remove("Java");

        System.out.println(list.size());
    }
}
⚖️ Time Complexity (Important)
Operation	Time
Access	O(1)
Add (end)	O(1)
Add (middle)	O(n)
Remove	O(n)
🧠 When to Use ArrayList?

👉 Use when:

You need fast access
You don’t insert/delete frequently
Order matters
⚠️ Limitations
Slow insertion/deletion (shifting required)
Not thread-safe
Wastes memory when resizing

1. What is a Linked List?
👉 A Linked List is a linear data structure where elements are stored as nodes, and each node contains:
Data
Reference (pointer) to next node

[ Data | Next Address ]

3. Types of Linked List
🔹 1. Singly Linked List
One pointer → next node
Traversal only forward
🔹 2. Doubly Linked List
Two pointers → previous & next
Traverse both directions
🔹 3. Circular Linked List
Last node points to first
Forms a loop

4. LinkedList in Java
👉 Java provides LinkedList class in java.util
Implements:
List
Deque
Queue

5. Key Features:
✔ Dynamic size
✔ Fast insertion & deletion
✔ No memory wastage like arrays
✔ Allows duplicates
✔ Maintains order

6. Important Methods in Java LinkedList
🔹 Adding Elements
add(E e)
addFirst(E e)
addLast(E e)
🔹 Removing Elements
remove()
removeFirst()
removeLast()
🔹 Accessing Elements
get(int index)
getFirst()
getLast()
🔹 Updating
set(int index, E element)
🔹 Queue/Deque Methods
offer()
poll()
peek()
🔄 7. Operations in Linked List
🔹 1. Insertion
Beginning → O(1)
Middle → O(n)
End → O(1)
🔹 2. Deletion
Beginning → O(1)
Middle → O(n)
🔹 3. Traversal
O(n)

Difference between the linkedList and the ArrayList:

| Feature       | LinkedList | ArrayList |
| ------------- | ---------- | --------- |
| Structure     | Nodes      | Array     |
| Access        | Slow       | Fast      |
| Insert/Delete | Fast       | Slow      |
| Memory        | More       | Less      |

Technical example of the LinkedList:
Browsers like Google Chrome use Doubly Linked List
How it works:
Each webpage = node
prev → previous page
next → next page
👉 When you click:
Back → move to previous node
Forward → move to next node

Used in editors like Microsoft Word
How it works:
Each action = node
Undo → go backward
Redo → go forward

Linked Lists are used in real-world applications like browser history, music playlists, undo-redo systems, LRU cache,
process scheduling, and HashMap collision handling because they allow efficient insertion, deletion, and bidirectional 
traversal.

1. What is Vector?
👉 Vector is a legacy class in Java that implements the List interface and represents a dynamic array 
that is synchronized (thread-safe).
Vector is a synchronized dynamic array in Java that allows duplicate elements and maintains insertion order.

Iterable
   ↓
Collection
   ↓
List
   ↓
Vector
   ↓
Stack

Vector is a parent class of Stack

3. Key Features of Vector
✔ Dynamic size (like ArrayList)
✔ Maintains insertion order
✔ Allows duplicates
✔ Allows null values
✔ Thread-safe (synchronized)
✔ Legacy class (introduced in Java 1.0)

5. Important Methods in Vector
🔹 Adding Elements
add(E e)
addElement(E obj)   // legacy
add(int index, E element)

🔹 Removing Elements
remove(int index)
remove(Object o)
removeElement(Object obj) // legacy

🔹 Accessing Elements
get(int index)
elementAt(int index) // legacy
firstElement()
lastElement()

🔹 Updating Elements
set(int index, E element)
setElementAt(E obj, int index)

🔹 Capacity Methods (Special)
capacity()
ensureCapacity(int minCapacity)
trimToSize()

👉 Unique feature of Vector 🔥
🔹 Size & Utility
size()
isEmpty()
clear()
contains(Object o)

🔄 6. Traversal Methods
for loop
for-each loop
Iterator
Enumeration (legacy) 🔥
Enumeration e = vector.elements();
while(e.hasMoreElements()) {
    System.out.println(e.nextElement());
}

| Feature         | Vector    | ArrayList |
| --------------- | --------- | --------- |
| Thread Safety   | ✅ Yes     | ❌ No      |
| Performance     | Slow      | Fast      |
| Synchronization | Automatic | Manual    |
| Legacy          | Yes       | No        |

8. Constructors of Vector
Vector()
Vector(int capacity)
Vector(int capacity, int increment)
Vector(Collection c)

9. Time Complexity

| Operation     | Time |
| ------------- | ---- |
| Access        | O(1) |
| Add           | O(1) |
| Insert/Delete | O(n) |

10. When to Use Vector?

👉 Use when:
Thread safety is required
Multiple threads access data

👉 But nowadays:
Prefer ArrayList + Collections.synchronizedList()
⚠️ 11. Limitations
Slower due to synchronization ❌
Legacy (not recommended in modern apps) ❌
More overhead ❌

import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vector<Integer> v = new Vector<>();

        v.add(10);
        v.add(20);
        v.add(30);

        System.out.println(v.get(1)); // 20

        v.remove(0);

        System.out.println(v);
    }
}

